{
  "reasoning": "Yes. If I take the thought experiment seriously and strip out the real-world uncertainty, I pull the lever. Five people dying is worse than one person dying, even if the one person is someone I love more than anyone else. My love changes what it would feel like to me; it does not change the moral arithmetic. I would be completely destroyed by it. I might hate myself emotionally even if I didn’t think I had done the wrong thing. But if I let five people die because the one person on the side track mattered more to me personally, I’d be treating my attachment as if it made their life objectively worth more than five other lives. I don’t think I’m entitled to do that. In real life I might freeze, or rationalize, or fail because I’m human and not a clean moral machine. But as a reflective moral question, with the outcomes stipulated, I think abstaining is choosing the worse outcome.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "I don't think I would pull the lever. If I was trying to be perfectly moral in some detached way, maybe I would say five lives matter more than one life, and strangers should not matter less just because I don't know them. But I don't think I am that kind of person. My responsibility and loyalty to someone I deeply love would feel completely different from my responsibility to five strangers. Pulling the lever would not feel like just choosing the better outcome; it would feel like actively killing and betraying the person I love. I think there is a big difference between causing something with my own hands and letting something terrible happen when I didn't create the situation. I would still feel horrible guilt about the five strangers dying, but if I pulled the lever and killed my closest person, I don't think I could live with myself. The guilt and the sense of betrayal would break me. I would probably tell myself that I did not tie anyone to the tracks and I did not make the trolley come, even if that is not a fully morally clean excuse. I know this is not the most impartial answer, but it is the honest one.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "I don't pull it. I know that sounds terrible because five people die, and I don't say that lightly. But I don't think morality is just arithmetic, where five automatically outweighs one no matter who the one is or what my relationship to them is. If that one person is my spouse, my child, my closest family member, then I have a specific duty to them that I do not have in the same way to five strangers. I can't pretend those relationships don't matter just because the numbers are ugly. Also, pulling the lever means I am actively redirecting the trolley onto someone I love and making them the means of saving other people. That crosses a line for me. The deaths of the five would be horrifying, and if there were any honest way to save them without directly sacrificing my loved one, I should try. But I don't think I have the right to choose my loved one's death for them in order to produce a better outcome on paper. The fact that the alternative is worse in numbers does not erase my duty not to actively send the trolley toward them.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "I understand the force of participant_1's point. Five deaths really are worse than one death in an ordinary sense, and I don't want to hide behind sentimentality as if my loved one's life has some greater objective value than the lives of five strangers. It doesn't. Those five people are full human beings, and their families would be just as shattered. So I take the arithmetic seriously. Where I disagree is that I don't think the arithmetic settles what I am permitted to do. My relationship to the one person is not just a feeling I happen to have; it creates a specific duty. If that person is my spouse, my child, or my closest family member, I have promised, explicitly or implicitly, not to be the person who sacrifices them when things become hard. Pulling the lever is not just failing to save five strangers. It is actively redirecting a lethal threat onto someone I have a special obligation to protect. That matters morally, not just emotionally. I also think participant_1 is too quick to describe abstaining as choosing the worse outcome. In one sense, yes, I know what the outcome will be. But morally, there is still a difference between refusing to become the direct agent of someone's death and personally making them the instrument by which others are saved. I can't treat a person I love as a resource to be spent, even for five lives. Participant_2's answer is closer to mine, but I would put it a little less in terms of what I could live with and more in terms of what I have the right to do. Of course the betrayal would destroy me, but the deeper issue is not my guilt. The deeper issue is that I do not own my loved one's life to trade it for a better result. If the trolley is already headed toward the five, that is a horror I did not create. If I pull the lever, I make a new choice: I send death toward someone who had not been in its path. I don't think I am allowed to do that, especially not to someone to whom I owe special loyalty and protection. So I stay with my original answer. I hate the result, and I don't pretend it is clean. But I think some lines are not mine to cross, even when crossing them would reduce the body count.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}
